HENDRA VIRUS, EQUINE - AUSTRALIA (17): (QUEENSLAND, NEW SOUTH WALES)
********************************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Mon 25 Jul 2011
Source: ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-07-24/hendra-suspected-in-chinchilla-horse-death/2807900


Hendra virus outbreak confirmed in Chinchilla
---------------------------------------------
Authorities in Queensland have confirmed another case of Hendra virus
on the western downs. Test results have confirmed a horse that died in
Chinchilla on Friday [22 Jul 2011] had the virus. It is the 1st case
west of the Great Diving Range.

Queensland's chief health officer Dr Jeannette Young says it is
unclear how many people had contact with the horse at this stage. "All
people who've had contact will have blood tests taken now, and again
in 21 days, and 42 days to just check that they haven't developed the
disease," she said. Dr Young says it is believed the vet who treated
the animal was wearing protective equipment.

"We've got staff out at the property now. They've only just arrived
but my initial understanding is that the vet who was involved with
this horse out at Chinchilla was wearing [protective clothing] but
we'll talk to the vet and just confirm that," she said.

It is believed there are 4 other horses on the property.

There have now been 8 outbreaks of Hendra virus in Queensland this
year [2011]. 9 horses in Queensland and 4 in New South Wales are
confirmed to have died from the disease over the past month.

The disease can be fatal in humans and authorities are currently
monitoring 51 people for signs of the illness.

Four of the 7 people to have ever contracted Hendra virus have died
from the disease.

